[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You using AI isn\'t the problem. You using AI to crank out soulless garbage at scale, that\'s the problem. If you\'re an author, creator, writer, and you secretly know that your AI content is starting to smell like everyone else\'s'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'beige sludge, this video is for you. I\'m going to give you seven rules so that you can use AI like a power tool, not a slop factory. So, let\'s go. My name is Jason Hamilton, and I built my career so'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'far on this concept of leverage, aka finding ways to do more or do better with less. AI is just the newest form of leverage. The losers are using it to ship more trash faster. The winners use'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it to do more thinking per unit of time and let the robot do the grunt work. So, here are the seven rules. Rule number one, you do the thinking, AI does the labor. AI is not allowed to decide what'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this piece is about, what your book is about. You decide who your readers are, what your story is about, what promise you are making to the readers, and then only then do you open the AI tools. Most authors think that AI is a replacement'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for the human mind, but that actually could not be further from the truth. If you are using AI to do your thinking for you, you will atrophy as a storyteller and as a writer. Instead, use AI to do'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'labor, aka the mechanical act of getting words on a page, but always guided by your thought. Thinking is ultimately the most important part of any art, whereas'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the actual mechanical parts of it are a separate skill. Those skills can be important to learn as well, but they are not the same as the thinking aspect of the art. I get accused all the time of not being a writer because I use AI, and'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at a certain level they might actually be right because the mechanical act of writing is something that I hand off to the machine. Instead, I consider this a totally new form of storytelling, one where I specialize more in the thinking'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'part and spend more of my time on that, and then let the AI do the actual typing. Rule number two is that AI plus a human will always beat AI by itself. If someone can replace their brain with'

[02:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a bot, they were replaceable anyway. And I don\'t care how good AI gets in the future, I will go to my grave insisting that an AI plus a human will always be better than AI by itself. Just like'

[02:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collaborating with a co-writer usually makes your books better, assuming you have a decent co-writer. Now, I take this further to say that AI plus a skilled human will always be better than AI plus an unskilled human, meaning it\'s'

[02:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still important to study craft and the art of writing, even if you\'re using AI, because a skilled writer knows what to fix, how to prompt better, and what kind of book to even start writing in the'

[02:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first place. An unskilled writer doesn\'t know what they don\'t know. So, make sure you\'re always striving to improve as a writer and a storyteller, which is something we do in my Story Hacker membership, where we have a periodic'

[03:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'writing challenges designed to upgrade the human, not the AI. Rule number three is to use AI for volume and use you for judgment. And rule number three is where we separate adults from children. AI\'s'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'superpower is volume. Your superpower is judgment. Most authors are playing this game like, "I\'ll spend 3 days trying to come up with the perfect plot, the perfect hook, the perfect blurb, and if it doesn\'t'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'show up, I guess I\'ve got writer\'s block." No, you are not blocked. You\'re running one experiment a week and calling that effort. Here\'s how you fix it with AI. Instead of you trying to think of one'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hook, you say, "Give me 20 possible hooks for this book that are curiosity-driven. Now, give me 20 that are promise-driven. Now, give me 20 that are controversy-driven." Instead of one blurb, you say, "Write 10 blurbs each with a different angle, like'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'emotional, logical, humorous, dark, high stakes, that sort of thing." Instead of one plot outline, you say, "Outline this book three different ways, like maybe as a mystery or as a hero\'s journey plot'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or as a romance-heavy version." Now, in 10 to 15 minutes, you\'ve got 30 to 60 options sitting in front of you, and this is where you come in. You scroll through and highlight the two to three best hooks, merge the best blurbs'

[04:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into a kind of Franken-blurb that actually makes really good sense, take the best outline and tweak it with your instincts and craft, etc. AI gives you volume, you decide what survives. This'

[04:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is exactly how professionals work in every creative field. Comedians write 100 jokes to keep 10. Marketers will write 50 headlines to keep five. We should be doing the same with titles,'

[04:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'blurbs, plots, scenes, every part of the book writing process. The amateur wants to be right on the first try. The pro assumes the first 90% is trash and just gets through it'

[05:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'faster. Give me 10 seconds. If you want to help cranking out way more books with AI, join the Story Hacker AI waitlist below. While the group\'s closed, I\'ll send you my full prompt pack for free. Click the link, enter your email, and'

[05:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll shoot it over. Let AI accelerate the bad draft phase so you can spend more of your time on the small percentage of things that are actually good. Rule number four is to never use AI\'s default voice, and you'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know exactly what I mean. Robotic transitions like furthermore and a testament to, cliche phrases like in today\'s fast-paced world, over-explaining every single emotion like your reader is 5'

[05:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'years old and concussed, and that\'s default AI, beige, polite, frictionless, and forgettable. So, how do we avoid that? Well, I\'ve got three things. First, feed it your real voice. Start with a few pieces of writing where you'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually sound like yourself writing that you\'re proud of, and dump those into the AI and say, "Analyze my style. What stands out about my word choice, sentence structure, tone, all of that? Summarize it in bullet points." Right?'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, then you get something like, "Okay, so you\'ve got short, punchy sentences and a casual, slightly snarky tone, lots of concrete examples, almost no big, fancy words." And you have it give you examples of all'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of those things. And then you paste that into your AI-generated draft and say, "Rewrite this in my style." Or if if you\'re starting your first draft, say, "Write this in my style following these bullet points. Keep the ideas, but make'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it sound like the samples." Now, the machine isn\'t pulling from its generic training data, it\'s pulling from you. Second, teach it what slop looks like. Literally Google the most common signs that text was written by generic AI, and'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll get a checklist of cringey things. Then ask the AI to scan this chapter and highlight any sentences that match those patterns. And then third, make sure to actually edit the thing yourself. AI can only get you so far.'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You have to take the reins eventually. Rule five is that serving the reader is king. Rule five might actually be the most important one in the whole video. We want to serve the reader, not serving'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the algorithm, not serving your own ego, not serving your word count streak, serving the reader. Your reader does not care if the words came from your hands, your keyboard, a'

[07:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dictation microphone, or your prompts, generally speaking. They care if they feel something, they learn something, they escape something,'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or their life improves in some clear way. That\'s more for nonfiction people. When people use AI badly, it\'s because they flip the focus to something more like, "How fast can I get this book done?"'

[07:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Instead of, "How much value can I deliver on every page?" So, here are two practical tests that I suggest that you run on everything you publish. Test number one is the $10 test. Look at your chapter or your whole'

[08:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'book and ask yourself, "If a stranger charged me $10 for this book, would I feel ripped off or grateful?" If you\'d feel ripped off, guess what? Your reader is paying with time, which'

[08:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is more scarce than $10. Make it so good that they feel lucky to have found it. Test number two is the review mirror. This is assuming you\'ve published it and'

[08:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you already have some reviews built up. Your reviews are not just compliments or insults, they\'re actually data that you can use as you go through and get that that feedback loop. If you see, "This felt generic" or "There\'s nothing new'

[08:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here" or "Skimmed a lot, didn\'t feel like it went too deep," those are not personal attacks, that is the market saying your value per page is low. And that\'s the case of your review status overall. So, fix it. Use AI to'

[08:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'help you respond. Summarize the main criticisms in these reviews. Or you could say, "Given these, suggest five specific ways to increase depth, specificity, or emotion in this chapter."'

[09:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Or help me add three concrete examples or stories that would address these complaints directly. Then you go in and actually do the work. Add the story, deepen the idea, sharpen the advice, because so many authors treat AI like a'

[09:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hallucination machine when they should be using it as a feedback amplifier, faster loops to serve the reader better. The bottom line is that AI is allowed to make your books faster, but it is never'

[09:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'allowed to make your books worse. Rule number six is to trust, but verify. AI sounds very sure of itself. That doesn\'t mean it\'s always right. And the danger with being an author is your words feel'

[09:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more permanent. When something\'s wrong in your book, nobody\'s going to say, "Well, maybe they were just using AI. We should treat them fairly." They\'re going to think you are just sloppy. So, the policy is let AI propose, you verify,'

[09:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then here\'s what that looks like in practice. For anything with a lot of facts and statistics, if AI gives you a statistic, you don\'t copy-paste it into your book. You go look them up. If you can\'t verify it, you cut it, rephrase it'

[10:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as a loose observation instead of a hard fact, or you just remove it entirely. For how-to steps, you might ask AI to outline a step-by-step process for X. Great, but then you say, "Now list'

[10:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'possible ways that this could go wrong in the real world." That kind of thing. You use AI to help you debug your own advice, not just generate more of it. For story logic in fiction, you can ask'

[10:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things like, "Read this plot summary. Point out any plot holes, character inconsistencies, or places a reader might feel cheated." Ultimately, you are still the final judge, but you\'re letting the machine play devil\'s'

[10:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'advocate at high speed. The mindset here is simple. AI is your bold brainstormer, and you are the paranoid editor. You want both. You want the crazy ideas and a strong filter.'

[10:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The second you let AI be both the idea generator and the fact-checker, you\'re done. And that\'s when hallucinations sneak in, and your readers\' trust falls off a cliff. Protect your name. Use AI to accelerate ideas, not to outsource'

[11:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'responsibility. Last rule, AI is leverage, not a replacement for work. This is the uncomfortable one, because if we\'re honest, a lot of people are excited about AI because they think it means'

[11:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they can finally skip the hard part and ever have everything be easier. But that\'s not the case. This is the uncomfortable one, because if we\'re honest, a lot of people are excited about AI because they think it means they can finally skip the hard'

[11:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'part. No more staring at the blank the blank page, wrestling with ideas, rewriting bad scenes, feeling dumb when you learn a new skill. Just type a prompt, wait 30 seconds, hit publish, make millions.'

[11:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That fantasy is why so much AI content feels like slop. But here\'s the truth. The painful parts of writing that actually build your skill, those are still required. What AI changes is how many reps you can get through, not'

[12:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whether you have to do them. Let me give you a concrete workflow that treats AI like leverage instead of a babysitter. Phase one is the thinking, which will take you 20 to 30 minutes. In this stage, you decide what this'

[12:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chapter or scene is really about. Jot down key beats or arguments, pull from your own life or your obsessions. And this is you doing the actual creative'

[12:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work. This is where the art lives. Phase two is the text generation, which is another 20 to 30 minutes. Now you bring in AI. "Turn those bullet points into three different outlines," you'

[12:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'might say. "Or draft a scene based on this summary. Give me one version that\'s lighter and one that\'s darker. Give me 10 alternative lines for this key moment, each with a different emotional tone." So AI is not inventing'

[12:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from nothing. It\'s spinning variations on what you already decided matters. Then phase three is the editing, which is an additional 30 to 40 minutes. You\'ll spend a little bit more time on this, because you as you go back'

[13:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through, you want to delete the 50% that feels wrong or boring, rewrite the 20 to 30% that\'s close but not quite you, and then keep the 10 to 20% that is surprisingly good. Run a remove the AI slop pass that we'

[13:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talked about in rule four. Same 60 to 90 minutes that you might have spent on that day wrestling with just one draft, but now you get through five or 10 times as much with the same amount of time. But you still did the'

[13:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uncomfortable part. You still made decisions, threw away work, held yourself to a higher standard. That\'s the stuff that makes you ultimately dangerous over a one to five-year time horizon. AI will absolutely expose'

[13:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whether you were serious about becoming a great storyteller or just chasing the path of least resistance. If you are serious, this is the best time ever to be an author. You get the leverage of a robot army'

[13:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with the taste and heart of a human. If you\'re not serious, AI will just help you fail faster and louder. So let\'s recap the seven rules of using AI without becoming slop factory. Number one is you do the thinking, AI'

[14:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'does the labor. The soul of the story is still your job. Number two, AI plus a human will always beat AI alone, especially if AI is paired with a skilled human.'

[14:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Number three is to use AI for volume and use you for judgment. So 10 hooks, 10 blurbs, three outlines, and then you pick the winners. Number four is never use AI\'s default voice. Instead, train it on your style,'

[14:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'teach it what slop looks like, and get specific with your tone. Number five is serving the reader is king. If it doesn\'t make their life better, it doesn\'t ship. Number six is trust but verify. Let AI propose, but you own the facts, the logic, and the'

[14:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'responsibility. And finally, number seven is AI is leverage, not a replacement for work. It multiplies your effort. It does not excuse you from hard work. If you follow these seven, you won\'t just avoid becoming a slop factory. You\'ll be one'

[15:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the rare authors who can publish faster, publish more, and publish higher-quality books. And if you\'re listening to this thinking, "Okay, I get it in theory, but I want help actually doing this with my'

[15:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'books," that\'s literally why I built my membership. In inside, we run writing challenges to upgrade the human, not just upgrading the prompts. And we give you tested AI workflows for planning, drafting, revising as much as'

[15:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '12 books a year. And we surround you with other serious authors who care about quality and speed. So if you want to be an author who uses AI like a power tool instead of a content vending machine, check out the'

[15:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'link in the description, come hang out with us, and let\'s build a catalog of books that you\'re not embarrassed by in five years. Because AI isn\'t going away. The only question is whether you let it turn you'

[15:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into a slop factory, or you use it to become the most prolific, high-quality version of yourself that you\'ve ever been. Your move.'
